
[1]brick

   BRICK, n. [L. imbrex, a gutter-tile, from imber, a shower, which is
   probably a compound, of which the last syllable is from whence.]

   A mass of earth, chiefly clay, first moistened and made fine by
   grinding or treading, then formed into a long square in a mold, dried
   and baked or burnt in a kiln; used in buildings and walls.

   1. A loaf shaped like a brick.

                   BRICK, v.t. To lay or pave with bricks.

   1. To imitate or counterfeit a brick wall on plaster,by smearing it
   with red ocher and making the joints with an edge-tool, filling them
   with fine plaster.
